<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Four-Day Cease-Fire Accord Signed in Kabul </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2102144594 Islamabad PTV Television Network in English 
1400 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2102144594 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad PTV Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Afghanistan, the forces loyal to President 
Borhanoddin Rabbani and Premier Golboddin Hekmatyar have agreed 
to another four-day cease-fire in Kabul. The cease-fire will 
come into effect from tomorrow morning. A member of the Islahi 
Shura [Reformation Council] told AIP [AFGHAN ISLAMIC PRESS] in 
Jalalabad that during the cease-fire, roads leading to the 
Afghan capital will be opened for traffic to enable the vehicles 
carrying foodstuffs and medicines to reach Kabul. The 
cease-fire has been brokered by the six-member delegation of 
Rabata al-Alam al-Islami [World Muslim League] and Islahi Shura 
of Afghanistan. An APP report says both President Rabbani and 
Premier Hekmatyar have agreed to the cease-fire. 

</TEXT>

