<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Rival Factions Resort to `Heavy Fighting' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK2002092794 Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service in 
English 0800 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK2002092794 </F>
<F P=104>  Islamabad Radio Pakistan Overseas Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Afghanistan, rival warring factions resorted to 
heavy fighting last night after a five-day uneasy calm. The 
fighting, which was the heaviest during the last fortnight, 
continued throughout the night and gradually died down in the 
morning. The two sides used heavy artillery and rocket fire on 
each other's positions in Bala Hesar, (Tapamaranjan), 
(Tivihilloc), Takatu, and (Omryan). The presidential palace in 
Kabul and Prime Minister Golboddin Hekymatyar's headquarters in 
Chahar Asiab also came under heavy fire. 
  Meanwhile, efforts are continuing to search new avenues for 
peace in Kabul. 
  Iranian officials have begun distribution of relief supplies 
to Afghan refugees in tents in Jalalabad. The supplies were 
flown to Peshawar and were taken to Jalalabad by road. The head 
of Iran's aid operation for Afghanistan said his country also 
plans to give supplies to Kabul once the city's airport is 
reopened to cargo planes. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

