<F P=100> ARAB AFRICA </F>
<F P=101> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Bosnian Situation With Cetin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2002184894 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1535 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2002184894 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 20 Feb (MENA)--Foreign Minister 'Amr Musa 
today telephoned his Turkish counterpart, Hikmet Cetin, and 
reviewed with him the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. This was 
disclosed by Minister Musa, who pointed out that Egypt and 
Turkey are holding constant consultations over this issue. 
  Answering a question on the approaching deadline given to 
the 
Bosnian Serbs with regard to weapons withdrawal from Sarajevo, 
the Egyptian foreign minister told news reporters that the Serbs 
will have to withdraw all their heavy weapons to a distance of 
20 km from Sarajevo. The removal of heavy guns, he added, 
should be comprehensive and not partial. 
  The foreign minister said that in the case of the partial 
withdrawal of weapons, the NATO's responsibility will continue. 
With the expiration of the deadline, Musa said, one of two 
things should take place: either the total withdrawal of all 
guns or a strike at Serbian positions. 
  Asked about the situation in other parts of Bosnia, Minister 
Musa said that decisions concerning Sarajevo should be 
applicable to other besieged areas of Bosnia. 
  Concerning his meeting with the Israeli ambassador in Cairo 
today, Minister Musa said that the meeting dealt with the 
Palestinian-Israeli talks that will be held in Cairo tomorrow, 
Monday. 
  Asked about reports of agreements or security arrangements 
reached between Iran and some Gulf countries and how such a 
development would affect the Damascus Declaration, Minister Musa 
said that these arrangements are still just news reports. The 
Egyptian foreign minister said that there is no indication of 
official movement in this direction. 

</TEXT>

