<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Arab-Israeli Talks </F>
<H3> <TI>   Sha'th Reports `Measure of Progress' in Taba </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  JN1802150994 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1030 GMT 18 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN1802150994 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Telephone interview with Nabil Sha'th, head of the </F>
Palestinian delegation to the Taba talks, in Cairo, Egypt, by 
Sa'id Mu'addi in the studio, from the "With the Midday Events" 
program; date not given -- recorded] 
  [Text] [Sha'th] I think this week's negotiations, which 
concluded in Taba yesterday, were positive and made some measure 
of progress. We would like our talks to lead to implementation 
on the ground so that ordinary Palestinians may come to feel 
real change. We have wrapped up discussions on a significant 
portion of the issues bearing on the transfer of civilian powers 
to the national Palestinian authority. The water issue remains 
to be addressed. We have finished with the issues of 
archaeology, regional planning, and wire and wireless 
communications. An agreement on relevant papers will be worked 
out next Monday here in Cairo. We also had exhaustive 
discussions concerning the release of Palestinian detainees. 
After the Red Cross team's visit to Taba, we now have all the 
relevant papers and figures. I believe that next Monday will 
see us achieve further progress. We also agreed in principle on 
launching a Palestinian television station and radio station on 
the medium wave. Regarding the Security Committee, it looked at 
a draft report on the composition of Palestinian police and 
security arrangements in the Gaza Strip and the Jericho region. 
I believe that progress was also made there. However, there 
are numerous points that need to be cleared by the political 
leaders. We will wait until next week to see progress made 
there. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil, have you begun drafting the points on 
which agreement was reached so that they may be presented to 
your respective political leaders? 
  [Sha'th] We are now formulating everything. There is no 
time left for discussions in a vacuum. All our negotiations 
address papers, item by item. 
  [Mu'addi] Do you see the outstanding issues being resolved 
next week? 
  [Sha'th] As much as I would like this to happen, it is hard 
for me to predict that much. As I have said, the Israeli side 
looks at certain matters as being mere symbols of sovereignty, 
while, in fact, they are highly significant symbols of national 
Palestinian identity and the national Palestinian authority. 
Things like passports, postage stamps, an international 
telephone code, and other such issues are essential to the 
Palestinian character and entity, even though these do not, as 
yet, imply the existence of a Palestinian state, because the 
Palestinian state has still to come into being. 
  [Mu'addi] Do you expect an agreement on all issues to be 
finalized by 'Id al-Fitr [on or about 13 March]? 
  [Sha'th] That is what I hope will happen. It would then be 
glad news for our people that will make the 'Id doubly happy. 
  [Mu'addi] Dr. Nabil Sha'th, the chief Palestinian negotiator 
in Taba, Thank you so much. 
  [Sha'th] Thank you. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35246 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes035cc_94001" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-NES-94-035 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  22 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

