<F P=100> Palestinian Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Hawatimah: PLO Leadership Opposes Accord Referendum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2202193394 Jerusalem AL-QUDS in Arabic 20 Feb 94 pp 1, 18 </F>
<F P=103> TA2202193394 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem AL-QUDS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Rashid Hilal] </F>
  [Excerpt] Damascus, Ramallah -- Nayif Hawatimah, secretary 
general of the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine, 
has affirmed that his faction will continue to participate in 
the current Palestine National Council [PNC]. He said, however, 
that this participation hinges on a call to rebuild all PLO 
institutions on a democratic and elected coalition basis and 
with national common denominators. 
  In an interview with AL-QUDS, Hawatimah said that this basis 
will ensure a serious commitment to and compliance with the 
decisions of the PLO's legislative and executive institutions. 
Hawatimah disclosed that he had invited the Palestinian 
leadership to discuss the Oslo-Cairo agreement and hold a 
referendum over this agreement, but the invitation was turned 
down. Hawatimah said that he favors a historic settlement on 
the basis of two states -- one Arab Palestinian and the other 
Jewish Israeli -- in accordance with the Palestinian people's 
right to self-determination and the return of the refugees on 
the basis of UN Resolution 194. 
  He added: This is what I asked for in my recent meetings 
with U.S. and Russian delegations in Damascus. He said: In 
these meetings I called on the delegations to cooperate with us 
in holding a Palestinian referendum, inside and outside the 
occupied territories, on the Oslo-Cairo agreement. 
  Hawatimah said: We are calling for evolution toward popular 
legitimacy by convening popular conferences in the homeland and 
the diaspora. This should lead to the holding of a unified 
national conference which would draw up a political program and 
choose a new leadership -- in a spirit of democracy and 
criticism -- that enjoys the people's support. The conference 
would also elect a new National Council, which in turn would 
rebuild all PLO institutions on democratic and coalition bases. 
  Hawatimah indicated that the Palestinian negotiating 
leadership is refraining from convening the current PNC because 
most of the council members oppose the Oslo-Cairo agreement. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

