<H3> <TI>   Clashes Reported Between North, South; Reaction Noted </TI></H3>
<H4>   Units of Former Armies Involved </H4>
<F P=102> JN2102162194 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Arabic 1556 GMT 21 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> JN2102162194 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Clashes erupted in southern Yemen today between two 
units of the former north Yemeni and south Yemeni armies, 
despite the fact that a reconciliation accord was signed in 
Amman yesterday between Yemeni President 'Ali 'Abdallah Salih, 
former president of north Yemen, and his deputy 'Ali Salim 
al-Bid, former leader of south Yemen. The accord is designed to 
end the political crisis that has continued for several months 
in Yemen. 
  The Yemeni president and his deputy left the Jordanian 
capital separately this afternoon after holding a prolonged 
meeting with King Husayn of Jordan. 
  Security and political sources in Sanaa have said that 
troops 
and tanks affiliated with a unit of the former north Yemeni Army 
are besieging the city of Zinjibar in southern Yemen in the 
aftermath of clashes with troops affiliated with the former 
south Yemeni army. The clashes erupted after troops affiliated 
with the north Yemeni army attempted to detain a colonel 
affiliated with the south Yemeni Army at a military checkpoint. 
  Yemeni sources in Amman said at noon today that at least 
four 
persons were killed in the clashes between the two sides. 

</TEXT>

