<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Former al-Asad `Rival' Reportedly Freed From Jail </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2202142294 Paris AFP in English 1347 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2202142294 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amman, Feb 22 (AFP)--A one-time rival of Syrian 
President Hafiz al-Asad, General Ahmad al-Suwaydani, has been 
freed after spending 25 years in jail, a former inmate said here 
Tuesday [22 February]. 
  Mujalli Nasrawin, a Jordanian who used to be a member of the 
Ba'th party which rules Syria and Iraq, told AFP that 
al-Suwaydani was freed on Monday for health reasons. 
  Himself released from a Syrian jail after 22 years, Nasrawin 
had called Saturday on Damascus to free al-Suwaydani, expressing 
fears he might die in al-Mazzah prison after having suffered an 
attack of hemiplegia. 
  Al-Suwaydani, a Sunni Moslem, was army chief-of-staff on the 
side of Salah Jadid, whose Ba'th party faction clashed with 
al-Asad's in the late 1960s. 
  At that time al-Asad, an Alawite Moslem, was air force chief 
under president Nur-al-Din al-Atasi, a Sunni. 
  In 1968, al-Asad ousted al-Suwaydani, who was jailed a year 
later. In a 1970 coup, al-Asad overthrew al-Atasi to take over 
as president. 
  Al-Atasi was freed in April 1992 and died last December in a 
Paris hospital, while Jadid died last August in a Damascus jail. 
  Some 20 political prisoners have been in jail in Syria for 
more than 20 years, most of them arrested during al-Asad's coup, 
according to international human rights groups. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35285 </DOCNO>
