<H3> <TI>   U.S. Ambassador, Delegation Meet al-Hariri, Others </TI></H3>
<H4>   Al-Hariri Receives Entourage </H4>
<F P=102> NC1802135794 Shanayh Voice of the Mountain in Arabic 1230 
GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC1802135794 </F>
<F P=104>  Shanayh Voice of the Mountain </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Rafiq al-Hariri today received U.S. 
Ambassador Mark Hambley and a visiting U.S. military delegation. 
  After the meeting, the U.S. ambassador expressed his belief 
that there will be an opportunity for a truce in Lebanon. He 
said: What is certain is that the only road to peace in the 
region is through negotiations. He added that the United 
States, as well as the Lebanese Government and all other 
governments, wants to see a peaceful solution in Lebanon. 
  Ambassador Hambley said the U.S. military delegation and the 
prime minister discussed a cooperation program between Lebanon 
and the United States that began a year and a half ago and that 
the discussion dealt with some future moves. This visit, he 
remarked, is the first in a series of visits scheduled for the 
delegation. 
  Asked about the likely role of the delegation in the south, 
Hambley said: We have no details on this matter. No doubt the 
Lebanese Armed Forces will play a very important role in south 
Lebanon. We want to help the Lebanese Armed Forces so that they 
are fully equipped in the future. He referred to a technical 
training program in addition to some equipment the United States 
will provide for the Army. 

</TEXT>

