<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Iran </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tehran Views U.S.-North Korean-IAEA Relations </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2202094794 Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network in Persian 0445 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2202094794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tehran Voice of the Islamic Republic of Iran 
First Program Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Persian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by News Research and Commentaries Group] </F>
  [Text] North Korea has taken new steps on the eve of the 
assembly of the International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] heads 
in Vienna. On Monday [21 February] Pyongyang put forth new 
conditions for the inspection of its nuclear installations by 
the IAEA. Among these conditions is the date for this 
inspection. 
  North Korea has made the date of the inspection of its 
nuclear installations contingent on the progress in the 
U.S.-North Korean talks, which are to be held in New York. In 
North Korea's opinion, the precise date of the inspection should 
be in coordination with the date that the United States has set 
for its other decisions on North Korea. 
  Probably, Pyongyang wants all the aspects of the issue to be 
clarified before the inspection of its nuclear installations by 
the IAEA. It seems that what North Korea means by U.S. 
decisions is the cancellation of the joint military maneuvers by 
the United States and South Korea and U.S. economic assistance 
to North Korea. 
  At the same time, Pyongyang has announced that it has agreed 
only to a limited inspection of its nuclear installations and 
has threatened that if it is pressured to expand this inspection 
it will cancel its agreement with the IAEA. On the basis of 
this agreement, North Korea will allow the IAEA to inspect only 
seven of its nine nuclear bases. North Korea's objective behind 
this threat is to gain an IAEA guarantee from the very start 
that it will not apply pressure about the other two nuclear 
sites. The developments in the Korean peninsula will be 
determined by the IAEA's reply to North Korea. 
  Political analysts believe Pyongyang's new actions are a 
result of the pressure that the United States has placed on it 
through threats. Negative action leads to negative reaction, 
and as long as the United States ignores North Korea's wishes 
and intends to pressure that country, it will have no 
alternative but to retaliate. 
  At any rate, if the United States and the IAEA ignore North 
Korea's recent threat, the talks may reach an impasse. 
Moreover, Pyongyang will prevent an inspection by the IAEA. 
Thus, the crisis in the Korean peninsula will become more 
complicated and finding a solution will become more difficult. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-35314 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drnes036_s_94010" </HT>


