<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres on Cairo Talks, Christopher Shuttle Mission </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2202122894 Tel Aviv IDF Radio in Hebrew 1100 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA2202122894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv IDF Radio </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] The Israeli and PLO delegations met in Cairo 
this morning for another discussion of the security issues. The 
talks focused on the size of the Palestinian police. Later 
today, the committee dealing with the transfer of the civilian 
powers will hold its session. 
  After meeting the foreign minister of Malta, Foreign 
Minister 
Shim'on Peres said this morning that the Israeli-PLO talks in 
Cairo are making satisfactory progress. He refused to say 
whether the issue of collaborators is being discussed. Our 
political correspondent Udi Segal reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Segal] The next Arab League convention, 
which will be held in Cairo in March, will discuss an offer 
which will probably bring the Arab boycott against Israel near 
its end. According to the offer, each Arab country will be able 
to decide whether to end or continue the boycott on its own. 
  Political sources in Jerusalem believe that if such a 
resolution is made, it would be followed by the cancellation of 
the boycott by several important Arab countries such as, among 
others, Qatar, Oman, Bahrain, Tunisia, and Morocco. 
  At the same time next month, U.S. Secretary of State Warren 
Christopher will arrive on a Middle East shuttle mission seeking 
to attain a breakthrough on the Syrian track. Foreign Minister 
Peres this morning addressed himself to the issue of U.S. 
involvement in the political process: 
  [Peres] The U.S. involvement is not the same on all three 
tracks. The negotiations with the Palestinians today are, in 
the main part, held directly between the two sides. 
Negotiations with Jordan take place in Washington, and I would 
like to see a faster pace there. As for Syria, for all intents 
and purposes, the negotiations are at the very initial stages. 
We would like to see a breakthrough there. [passage omitted] 
[end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

