<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   IDF Withdrawal Completion Slated for May </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2302061894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in English 0500 GMT 23 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2302061894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] As the peace talks continue in several locations 
around the world, there is word here in Jerusalem that the IDF 
[Israel Defense Forces] withdrawal from Gaza and Jericho will be 
completed by the third week of May. Senior sources in Jerusalem 
gave this estimate to Qol Yisra'el correspondent Hayim Hecht. 
These sources say the May date has already been transmitted to 
Yasir 'Arafat. 
  On Jordan, the sources said, the talks in Washington are 
concentrating on preparing a full and detailed peace. 
  As far as the Palestinian police force is concerned, Israel 
is said to have agreed that it would be 8,500-strong, a 
compromise between the positions of both sides. According to 
the sources, once the agreement is actually signed, Israel will 
release more than 1,000 Palestinian prisoners. 
  [A report by On Levi on page 1 of Tel Aviv DAVAR in Hebrew 
on 
23 February adds that "the IDF had planned to free about 1,000 
Palestinian detainees on Sunday, 20 February, but canceled the 
move in the wake of the murder of Tzipora Sason near Ari'el on 
Friday night."] 
  Speaking earlier in Madrid, Prime Minister Yitzhaq Rabin 
said 
that when an agreement on Palestinian self-rule is signed 
between Israel and the Palestinians, the IDF withdrawal can be 
implemented within a few weeks. 
  [Begin Rabin recording] Since I do not know when we will 
reach the agreement, I can't give you any speculation about 
dates. But allow me to say: We would like that the 
implementation of the agreement will be done in a matter of a 
few weeks and not to be prolonged too long. [end recording] 
  The prime minister made the comment at a joint news 
conference yesterday in Madrid with his Spanish counterpart, 
Felipe Gonzalez. Rabin, on the third day of his four-day visit, 
arrives today in Portugal. 
  The head of Fatah in the West Bank, Faysal al-Husayni, says 
agreement will be reached with Israel on implementing the 
Gaza-Jericho-First accord by the April 13th deadline. 
Al-Husayni made the statement after meeting with the foreign 
minister of Malta, Guido de Marco. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 0500 GMT on 23 February 
adds that "Israeli and Palestinian negotiators in Cairo reported 
that progress was made in yesterday's talks. Chief PLO delegate 
Nabil Sha'th said that it is possible that Prime Minister Rabin 
and PLO leader 'Arafat will be able to meet by the end of next 
week."] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

