<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   High Turnout Reported in NRP Registration Campaign </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2002144194 Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ in Hebrew 20 Feb 94 p A6 </F>
<F P=103> TA2002144194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tel Aviv HA'ARETZ </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by party affairs correspondent Yerah Tal] </F>
  [Excerpts] Approximately 30,000 people have registered 
themselves in the framework of the special National Religious 
Party [NRP] registration campaign, which started on 15 November 
1993 and has just ended. NRP officials were surprised by the 
larger than expected turnout. According to NRP estimates, the 
number of registrants was expected to be far lower due to the 
campaign's low public profile. 
  NRP officials expressed the assessment that the relatively 
high turnout, which includes many new names, may lead to serious 
changes in the composition of the delegates to the NRP 
convention and in the party's list of candidates to the Knesset. 
The census was carried out prior to the internal elections for 
the party's convention and for the councils of the various 
branches, which will be held on 26 April 1994. [passage omitted] 
  The last NRP census was conducted seven years ago. That was 
also the last time the party held internal elections. 
  Since then, the NRP has twice postponed the census with the 
approval of the movement's tribunal. Once, because the date of 
national elections was brought forward, and a second time due to 
the local council elections. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

