<F P=100> SYRIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Al-Hirawi, al-Asad Discuss Peace, Other Issues </TI></H3>
<H4>   No `Separate Peace Accords' Pledged </H4>
<F P=102> JN2102193294 Manama WAKH in English 1645 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> JN2102193294 </F>
<F P=104>  Manama WAKH </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Damascus, Feb 21 (GNA)--Syrian President Hafiz 
al-Asad and Lebanese President Ilyas al-Hirawi agreed during 
their talks here on Sunday [20 February] to adhere to the 
principle of a comprehensive settlement in the region, reliable 
Syrian sources said. 
  The sources told Qatar News Agency that the two leaders also 
pledged not to sign a unilateral peace accord with Israel, and 
that progress should be achieved on all tracks. 
  The two leaders denounced Israeli attempts to reach separate 
peace accords with Arab states involved in the peace process and 
expressed strong support for the comprehensive peace formula 
based on UN Security Council Resolutions 242 and 338, the 
sources said. The sources noted that Syria emphasized that it 
was politically committed to working for the implementation of 
Security Council Resolution 425 calling on Israel to withdraw 
from southern Lebanon. 
  The sources said Syria has already turned down an Israeli 
offer to separate the question of the Israeli occupation of the 
Syrian Golan Heights from the Israeli occupation of south 
Lebanon, and at the same time, Syria reaffirmed that a balanced 
solution should be achieved on all tracks. 
  Syria has succeeded in convincing the United States, via 
recent contacts between Damascus and Washington, about the 
importance of implementing Security Council Resolution 425, the 
sources said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

