<F P=100> JORDAN </F>
<H3> <TI>   Abu-Nidal `Terrorists' Charged in Diplomat's Murder </TI></H3>
<H4>   AFP Reports 15 Arrests </H4>
<F P=102> NC2202144494 Paris AFP in English 1406 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2202144494 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Amman, Feb 22 (AFP) -- Jordanian police arrested 15 
alleged members of Abu-Nidal's Palestinian "terrorist" group 
which is suspected of having killed a Jordanian diplomat in 
Beirut, a judicial source said here Tuesday [22 February]. 
  The police on Saturday launched sweeps targeting Abu-Nidal's 
banned Fatah-Revolutionary Council movement, arresting fifteen 
persons and closing a trade office, the source told AFP. 
  The crackdown was decided after the Lebanese authorities had 
proved that Abu-Nidal's group was behind the killing of Jordan's 
embassy first secretary in Beirut, Na'ib al-Ma'ayitah, on 
January 29, the sources added. 
  Documents and propaganda leaflets were found in the trade 
office, located in the al-'Abdali neighborhood of the capital 
Amman. 
  Investigations are underway to determine if there is enough 
evidence to put the 15 on trial, the source said. 
  Most of the suspects have had already spent time in prison 
in 
the 1970s for their links to Abu-Nidal's group. 
  King Husayn on Feb 13 accused an Arab country of having 
ordered an extremist group whose leader lives in that country to 
carry out the murder. The king did not name the country but a 
Jordanian source said he was referring to Libya. 
  Tripoli has denied these accusations. 

</TEXT>

