<F P=100> Sudan </F>
<H3> <TI>   SPLA Reportedly Repels Government Brigade </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AB2302094694 Paris AFP in English 2116 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AB2302094694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Nairobi, 22 Feb (AFP) -- The rebel Sudan People's 
Liberation Army (SPLA) has claimed that its forces repulsed a 
huge government infantry brigade between Amadi and Lui offensive 
on February 12, capturing tanks, lorries and communications 
equipment. 
  A statement issued here Tuesday by John Garang's SPLA 
faction 
said its forces of Maridi-Mundri, reinforced by those from 
Rumbek, under the command of Gier Chuong Aluong and Jadallah 
Wani, destroyed two tanks, and 16 lorries, forcing the enemy to 
run in disarray. 
  During their flight, the government forces abandoned seven 
landrovers and four Toyotas mounted with heavy machine guns, 
ammunition of various categories and food, the statement said, 
adding that SPLA forces also captured a radio communication set 
and one of its operators, a man from the Nuba Mountains. 
  The Sudanese Government has persistently denied that its 
forces had mounted a major offensive in southern Sudan, where a 
bloody civil war has been raging since 1983 between government 
forces and southern rebels seeking to end domination of the 
mainly Christian and animist south by the Arabised Moslem north. 
Khartoum has instead said the fighting has been between the 
different faction of the SPLA, a claim that has been strongly 
denied by the southern rebels. 

</TEXT>

