<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Peres Addresses Committee on Impact of Arab Boycott </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2102112894 Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew 1100 GMT 21 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2102112894 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Foreign Minister Shim'on Peres has said that five 
Arab countries are currently working to cancel the Arab boycott 
against Israel. These countries are Egypt, Tunisia, Oman, 
Qatar, and Morocco. Peres stressed that the Arab boycott is as 
much a problem for the Arab world as it is for Israel. 
  Speaking before the Knesset Economic Affairs Committee, 
which 
discussed the effects of the Arab boycott on Israel, the foreign 
minister added that in its war against the Arab boycott, Israel 
is not seeking to take over the Arab world. Through the peace 
process, Israel is trying to bring about an economization of 
politics instead of a politicization of economics. This was 
reported by our correspondent Eytan Almog. 
  [Jerusalem Qol Yisra'el in Hebrew at 1105 GMT on 21 February 
adds that Foreign Minister Peres also said that "the economic 
aid Israel receives from the United States compensates for the 
losses incurred as a result of the Arab boycott."] 

</TEXT>

