<F P=100> ISRAEL </F>
<H3> <TI>   Police Minister: No Special Status for Orient House </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  TA2002192794 Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network in 
Hebrew 1800 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> TA2002192794 </F>
<F P=104>  Jerusalem New Channel 2 Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Hebrew </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpts] Tomorrow the Knesset Internal Affairs Committee 
will discuss the status of Orient House, the PLO's headquarters 
in East Jerusalem. The discussion will be held in the wake of a 
report aired here yesterday, in which the Jerusalem Police chief 
admitted that the building is outside the police responsibility. 
Internal Affairs Committee Chairman Yehoshu'a Matza has invited 
the police minister to tour the building. Our police 
correspondent Moshe Nussbaum reports: 
  [Begin recording] [passage omitted] A senior Orient House 
element today told us off the record that in recent secret 
contacts with Israeli officials, a clear understanding was 
achieved under which the building was granted an unofficial 
status of an embassy or a consulate. He confirmed that the 
security personnel had been ordered to ban Israeli policemen 
from the building. [end recording] 
  Police Minister Moshe Shahal said in reaction that Orient 
House has no special status, and that the police behave toward 
it as they do any other building. 

</TEXT>

