<F P=100> LEBANON </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cabinet Discusses Reshuffle, Economy </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2402092294 Beirut Voice of Lebanon in Arabic 0615 GMT 24 
Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2402092294 </F>
<F P=104>  Beirut Voice of Lebanon </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The cabinet yesterday discussed three issues that 
have not been announced. The first was the government situation 
and the attempt to reshuffle the cabinet portfolios based on 
certain plans by the president and the prime minister. These 
plans have clashed with calculations by the parliamentary 
speaker, who demanded the Finance Ministry portfolio for his 
sect based on the principle that any reshuffle must aim at 
energizing governmental work and that this can only be done by 
correcting the course of the state's financial policy, which has 
demonstrated its failure and sterility. While agreement between 
the president and the prime minister exists because of the 
indirect concurrence of interests, the sticky issue of 
reshuffling the portfolios persists. It affects the Ministries 
of Finance, Interior, Industry and Oil, and Labor. President 
Ilyas al-Hirawi and Prime Minister Rafiq al-Hariri raised this 
issue during their meeting with Syrian President Hafiz al-Asad. 
The two returned with a firm response from the Syrian 
leadership that it is ready to assist Lebanon in resolving 
problems in government work, but that a change of government or 
reshuffle is an internal Lebanese matter. Lebanese political 
sources maintain that a government reshuffle is still possible 
but will not be sufficient as the entire government performance 
in the political, economic, and security fields is deficient. 
  The second issue discussed by the cabinet was the high cost 
of living and economic stagnation. This is occurring at a time 
when the dollar rate in the local market has been stable and the 
government claims that the development and reconstruction 
process is continuing. This is casting some doubt on the 
state's financial policy. 
  The third issue was the demands of the General Labor 
Federation. With the federation's demands, a crisis has been 
created for political reasons. Some ministers at yesterday's 
cabinet session maintained that this fabricated crisis 
constitutes a crime against the worker and his livelihood and is 
a dangerous step at this time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

