<F P=100> Egypt </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bomb Explodes Aboard Cairo-Luxor Train </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  NC2302185194 Cairo MENA in Arabic 1810 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2302185194 </F>
<F P=104>  Cairo MENA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Arabic </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, 23 Feb (MENA)--An official security source 
has stated that at around 1430, a device placed on the overhead 
luggage rack in a first-class coach on train no. 980 went off as 
the train traveled from Cairo to Luxor. The explosion occurred 
as the train was passing the village of al-Muti'ah after leaving 
Asyut Station. 
  Some 11 passengers, including six tourists, were injured in 
the explosion. They include: Major Faysal Fattuh al-Wakil of 
Suhaj; Muhammad 'Abd-al-Hayy, a technician in the Arab 
Contractors Company; Faysal Fahmi Adam, an orthopedist at Asyut 
University; Lieutenant Jamal Ahmad Husayn, a resident of Suhaj; 
and Rif'at 'Abd-al-Majid, a train worker. The wounded tourists 
are Angel Ascot and Joe Fix, New Zealand; Ulrike Dolgan and 
Christian Schreiker, Germany; and Grace Casio and Jocelyn 
Clonita, Australia. They were all slightly hurt. All the 
wounded were taken to Asyut University Hospital for treatment. 
  The explosion occurred in the second coach on first class, 
damaging the coach roof and shattering windows. An initial 
examination of the train indicates that the shattered glass 
probably injured the passengers. 
  Leading officers in the Asyut Security Directorate, the 
criminology laboratory, and various detective agencies went to 
the scene and the prosecution was notified to launch an 
investigation. 
  Investigations are under way to determine the circumstances 
surrounding the incident. The train was sent on its way to 
Suhaj then Luxor after an inspection by explosives experts. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

