<F P=100> SOUTH ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Afghanistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   President Meets Pakistan's Foreign Minister </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402181394 Kabul Radio Afghanistan Network in Pashto 1530 
GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2402181394 </F>
<F P=104>  Kabul Radio Afghanistan Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Pashto </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Esteemed Professor Borhanoddin Rabbani, president of 
the Islamic State of Afghanistan, this morning received 
Pakistan's foreign minister, Sadar Asif Ahmad Ali. In the 
meeting, they discussed current issues and the need for the 
ensuring peace and security. Conversation and the exchange of 
views were also conducted on relations and cooperation between 
the two countries of Afghanistan and Pakistan. President 
Rabbani expressed regret and sorrow at the incidents in the 
embassies of the two countries. The Pakistani foreign minister 
emphasized the expansion and consolidation of relations and 
friendly cooperation between the two countries. He also said 
that the incidents which occurred in the embassies of the two 
countries would not have any impact on the relations of Pakistan 
with Afghanistan. In the meeting, he expressed the readiness of 
that country to cooperate to restore peace and security in 
Afghanistan and said: We do not tell the Afghanis what to do, 
and we are ready, at any moment, to play any role we can to 
resolve the problems of Afghanistan. He also said: We envision 
taking some measures to send food to Kabul. The Pakistani 
minister of foreign affairs thanked Afghanistan's security 
officials for preventing embassy officials from being killed 
during the incident at Pakistan's embassy in Kabul. Asif Ahmad 
Ali, who arrived in Kabul yesterday afternoon, left for his 
country this morning. At the end of his visit, he expressed 
pleasure with the result of his meetings and visit and said: The 
incidents that have recently occurred in the embassies of the 
two countries will not cause any change in the previous status 
of Afghan refugees who live in Pakistan, and we welcome, as in 
the past, Afghan refugees as our guests as long as they do not 
return to their homeland. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

